Abstract: Air fluorescence in the region 310 nm to 400 nm is due to nitrogen fluorescence.[1] We measured the nitrogen fluorescence yield in air as a function of pressure between 1.4 MeV and 1 GeV by means of a strontium fi source and an electron beam. The pressure dependency of nitrogen fluorescence is well described by a formula derived from simple kinetic theory. Results indicate that nitrogen fluorescence yield in air is proportional to electron energy loss from 1.4 MeV to 1 GeV. The dE/dx relativistic rise in air is detected.
